        ", serving as its first Secretary until 42     Jones undertook an intensive programme of writing and research, which produced the first of what were to be many significant contributions to psychoanalytic literature, notably monographs on  Hamlet  and On the Nightmare. A number of these were published in German in the main psychoanalytic periodicals published in Vienna; these secured his status in ": null
    },
    {
        "Freuds inner circle": "inner circle"
    },
    {
        " during the period of the latters increasing estrangement from Jung. In this context in 42 Jones initiated, with Freuds agreement, the formation of a Committee of loyalists charged with safeguarding the theoretical and institutional legacy of the psychoanalytic movement. This development also served the more immediate purpose of isolating Jung and, with Jones in strategic control, eventually manoeuvring him out of the Presidency of the ": null
    },
    {
        "International Psychoanalytical Association": "international psychoanalytical association"
    },
    {
        ", a post he had held since its inception. When Jungs resignation came in 42 it was only the outbreak of the Great War that prevented Jones from taking his place.     Returning to London in 42 Jones set up in practice as a psychoanalyst, founded the London Psychoanalytic Society, and continued to write and lecture on psychoanalytic theory. A collection of his papers was published as Papers on Psychoanalysis, the first account of psychoanalytic theory and practice by a practising analyst in the English language.     By 42 the year he founded the ": null
    },
